src_en_ctx: Remember? The story of Alzheimer's is never about one person. My PhD thesis film posits that this insidious disease not only destroys the patient, but has a physiological influence on the primary caregiver. Alzheimer's occurs when abnormal protein fragments accumulate in the hippocampus, killing neurons. The disease then creeps towards the front of the brain, wiping out neurons responsible for logical thought and problem solving. It then assaults the sensory region, sparking terrifying hallucinations.<brk> Eventually, it erases a person's oldest and most precious memories.

Ma thèse postule que cette maladie insidieuse détruit non seulement le patient, mais a une influence physiologique sur le soignant principal. La maladie d'Alzheimer se produit quand des fragments de protéines anormales s'accumulent dans l'hippocampe, tuant les neurones. La maladie se propage alors vers l'avant du cerveau, effaçant les neurones responsables de la pensée logique et de la résolution des problèmes. src_en: Unlike the outer planets of the solar system, the outer stars in the galaxy were all going at the same speed as the stars that were closer in, and they were moving way faster than expected.

src_en_ctx: The harder you push or pull on something, the faster it goes. The Sun's gravity weakens with increasing distance, so, the planets that are farther from the Sun move more slowly. Everyone expected that the outermost stars in a galaxy would act the same way. Most of the stars are concentrated towards the center, so, their collective gravity pulls on the other stars the same way the Sun pulls on the planets. But in the 1970s, when astronomer Vera Rubin studied the Andromeda Galaxy, she discovered that the outer stars obeyed no such rule.<brk> Unlike the outer planets of the solar system, the outer stars in the galaxy were all going at the same speed as the stars that were closer in, and they were moving way faster than expected.
tgt_fr_ctx: Plus vous poussez ou tirez sur quelque chose, plus elle s'accélère. La gravité du Soleil diminue avec la distance croissante, donc, les planètes qui sont plus éloignées du Soleil se déplacent plus lentement. Tout le monde s'attendait à ce que les étoiles ultrapériphériques d'une galaxie agissent de la même façon. La plupart des étoiles sont concentrées vers le centre, donc, leur gravité collective attire les autres étoiles de la même façon que le Soleil attire les planètes. Mais dans les années 70, quand l'astronome Vera Rubin étudia la galaxie d'Andromède, elle a découvert que les étoiles externes n'obéisaient pas une telle règle.<brk>
src_en_with_tags:
Unlike the outer planets of the solar system, the outer stars in the galaxy were all going at the same speed as the stars that were closer in, and

they
